umer fraudcomplaints in all 50 states charging four major publishers withselling achievement tests that give a misleadingly rosy picture ofstudent progress.   The complaints were filed Wednesday by John Jacob Cannell.   Cannell gained prominence last November as a test gadfly with a26-page report accusing publishers of the Iowa Test, theMetropolitan Achievement Test and similar tests of giving``children, parents, school systems, legislatures, and the pressmisleading reports on achievement levels.''</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Residents of mid-sized cities in the West nolonger will get detailed figures on monthly price changes in theircommunities.   In New York and Los Angeles, monthly household surveys ofemployment and unemployment are being cut back sharply. Tracking oftrends among blacks, Hispanics, teen-agers and women in the twocities will be less current.   The government is changing the numbers it collects and crunchesto measure whether times are good or bad.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market rose in a late rally Wednesday. The Dow Jonesaverage of 30 industrials closed 16.91 points higher at 2,064.32.   The dollar rose slightly against most major currencies. Goldprices edged lower in domestic trading after climbing overseas.   Bond prices tumbled on government reports indicating growth inthe economy.   Most grain and soybean futures prices turned weaker. Crude oilprices closed higher in a volatile session following reports ofunrest in Central America.</TEXT></DOC>